Where your world is tilted one way, and mine another.

In the same tongue our phrases span many maps, 
Where the cartography of boundaries is our fate, 
Where the rivers that bound us are now dammed,
Where my sky is a different shade of blue to yours,
Where the wind blows you one way, and me another. 

In the same tongue our phrases span many histories, 
Where time and space can no longer make us relate, 
Where the present and past are hostage to bloodlines, 
Where the future sums all our joys and miseries, 
Where we divide this nostalgia in half:
A piece of me for you, a piece of you for me.  


 

<Load>
The day she left it rained for seven days straight. It rained so hard that it was hard to think over the din of countless roofs being assaulted by the endless stream of watery bullets. In homes across Mirage, everyone took to talking louder so they could be heard over this monsoon rain which, some suggested, was caused by the First Ancestors seeking ablution in the heavenly waters above, while the more blasphemous joked crudely that Saman, Shiva and Adam were taking a long overdue piss after a cosmic night of drinking. During the week, Dev hardly ate, slept, or wrote as his mind and heart tried valiantly to be heard over the sound of the rain. One day, risking getting caught to the many floods that had brought the city to a virtual halt, Dev made his way to Anaka’s family home. As he approached it from the bridge near the lake that bordered the house, he could see that there was no way he could get any closer. Already the waters had overflown the banks of the lake and submerged the bottom third of the gate. Under the murky waters, he thought he could make out the shapes of fish, monitor lizards, and water snakes. 
Further misery followed when the weather changed. The rains had given new life to mosquitoes; within weeks, the country experienced a surge in dengue fever. Among the many people who contracted the disease was Dev, the new President’s youngest. In his delirious state of dropping platelet counts, non-existent appetite, raging fever, and intolerable body aches, Dev remembered brief moments of consciousness when he’d look around the room and find Ohiy watching over him. ‘There, there, baby boy’, her reassuring voice would soothe him. She’d have all manner of water and liquids for him to sip, which Dev struggled to gulp but would be coaxed into consuming. One night the fever and body ache got so bad, Dev was sure he was dying. His dry throat couldn’t make a sound, he found his breathing became belaboured; when he opened his eyes in panic he couldn’t tell if his eyes were opened or not, such was the impenetrability of the darkness that encroached every angle of his sight. Dev, bathed in sweat, surrendered to the pain. That’s when the face appeared, the same beatific radiance that was hard to forget. 
‘Come find me when you are well.’ 
Dev felt better the next morning. Though still sore and feeling unwell, he felt he had come through the worst; he was right. Over the next two weeks, as his vitals began showing improvement, Dev began to think of ways to see that face again. In moments when Ohiy left to attend to his grandmother, Dev would slip out of the bed and go into Manal’s old room. Rifling through his drawers, he found what he was looking for. 
He broke the bud into little pieces just as Manal had done that day a few months ago when he had offered him a puff. He filed the little pipe, lit it, and inhaled deeply. He still coughed but now he found himself enjoying the fits of coughing as his lungs heaved and with every heave it seemed to push his mind higher and higher to state that he believed was meditative. This new practice became a habit that birthed changes to his character. Dev began having an appetite. This wasn’t novel simply because he had recently recovered from a potentially lethal illness but because the youngest Mahasen had never shown an affinity for food before his entire life. Dev ate to get other people to stop pestering him to eat, not because he was hungry. He couldn’t recall ever having craved for any food before, but here for the first time in his young life, he was hungry; milk-rice, lentil pancakes with beef stew, flatbread with cassava, and jackfruit broth quickly became his favourites. Ohiy, used to a life time of having to force Dev to eat, was first pleased, then bemused, and finally suspicious but allowed Dev to be free of any prying. A month after his close encounter with death, Dev had put on so much weight that his still-teenage body found itself confused with this sudden addition of mass. The herb had numbed the pain of losing Anaka but was no closer to revealing that face again. Dev would learn years later in the future that it had also opened the doors for depression. 
‘I think’, Ohiy began one day as she folded his clothes into the closet, ‘that it’ll be a good idea now for you to get some fresh air. You’ve been caged inside this room for weeks now.’ 
Dev was stoned when she had entered the room and tried his best to act normal. 
‘I said, it’d be a good idea for you to get some fresh air’, Ohiy repeated. 
‘Yes’, Dev squawked. His throat was dry and his tongue parched. He had an urge to yawn even though it was barely afternoon. 
‘Is there any place you want to visit inside the country? The city is dry and horrid if I am perfectly honest – go to the country!’
Before he could answer, Dev remembered Rejog’s words from his death bed. ‘I like being caged in too much, don’t I?’, he found himself saying. 
‘You do’, Ohiy said, turning around in surprise. 
‘I need to find someone, Ohiy.’ 
Ohiy thought the youngest Mahasen had meant a love interest. She was happy thinking that Dev had overcome his first heart-break already. ‘Lots of nice girls who’d want a nice smart boy –‘
‘- that’s not what I meant, Ohiy. I need to find a priest.’ 
Ohiy thought she had misheard. ‘What now?’ 
Dev’s intoxication had ricocheted him from paranoia and silence to an open talkativeness that made the old woman who had raised him from his first day tilt her head in suspicion. She examined his face while Dev tried smiling stupidly in hopes of deflecting the inevitable interrogation. 
‘Why are your eyes swollen and red?’
‘I just, err, woke up –‘
‘Don’t lie to me, boy. You are no good at it. Your brothers were better but I still caught them every time’, she said as she walked closer and sniffed around his face. ‘So’, she sighed, ‘you found Manal’s herb.’ 
Dev looked down, unable to face her. 
‘Suppose it could be worse. This led your brother to that thing he calls music. It’s leading you to explore your faith. You understand this is unusual in your family, no?’ 
Dev nodded. 
‘I can talk to your father and arrange for a meeting with Prophet –‘ 
‘- no’, Dev interrupted. ‘Not him. I met this one at the Temple of Butterflies.’ 
‘Those aren’t priests, Dev - they are hermits. These are fools who run away-’ 
‘- I know what a hermit means, Miss Ohiy. I know who I want to meet.’ 
Ohiy sighed again, turned around and walked away saying ‘I suppose it could be worse’ to no one in particular. 
A week later Dev made the climb up Peak to the Temple of Butterflies. 
Each step felt heavy with nostalgia of that first time with Anaka by his side. Like the first time, the mist covered the temple. Like the first time, Dev climbed days after the Fourth Moon. Unlike the first time, he was truly alone. The wind howled in his ear. His lungs begged for him to stop. Four hours later, Dev was on his hunches and breathing heavily, lost in a heavy mist that had now enveloped everything around him. Visibility reduced to inches, sometimes not even that. Dev lifted his hands in front of his face and lost sight of them for several seconds as the mist weaved between and around of his fingers. Unable to see the sun, unable to see the step ahead or the step behind, unable to see his own hands, and bullied by the wind that now pushed him from every direction, Dev sat down just as the thunderstorm started. The rain felt like pebbles being fired by a cruel child god, but it was the bolts of lightning that terrified Dev the most. With no rain coat or protection, Dev had little choice but to crouch and make himself as small as possible, and hope for the best. It’d be half a day before the storm cleared. When it did, Dev felt the warm heat of the sun from well above the horizon – it was almost noon.  
He was wet and miserable but saw no point in heading back after going through such an ordeal. An hour or so later, he climbed the last step and collapsed at the gates to the Temple of Butterflies, and woke to the sensation of a dog licking his face. 
The hermit was standing over him and the dog. 
‘You did it’, Gaudharma Brunhha, the beatific hermit smiled. ‘You found me, Dev.’ 
　　　　***

Gaudharma Brunhha
-From Circadipedia, the free encyclopedia 
Gaudharma Brunhha <September 15th 2563 - September 15th 2619[again, Gregorian calendar? ]>1 was a Circadian hermit, philosopher, neuroscientist, computer scientist and polymath2. He was best known for his pioneering research into the epistemological limits of human cognition3, and his seminal paper Consciousness And Code, with an application to mental health of adults suffering from depression, social isolation and loneliness4. He was also widely known for interests and contributions in other fields, including mathematics [citation needed], physics5 and psychology6, having formed highly productive collaborative relationships with public intellectuals in these fields, particularly JvN Nagas7 with whom he worked on building upon the theory of quantum Darwinism, proposed five centuries ago by theoretical physicist Wojciech Zurek8. 
Brunhha’s life as a public intellectual came to a sudden halt when he was reported missing by his wife Ailuja Atta-Brunhha in the early hours of September 15th 25999. A nationwide search for Brunhha was launched the next day. He was found alive and well three weeks later while meditating in a jungle. Brunhha refused to leave and threatened suicide if any attempt were made to forcefully take him back to his home10. 
Brunhha died alone in his sleep on September 15th [are we using gregorian calendar? ]261911, exactly twenty years to the day of his self-imposed exile, exactly on the day he would have turned fifty-six. 
