Life
Early life and education 
Gaudharma Brunhha was born in New Konik, Circadia. His father, Aloc Brunhha, was the heir to the New Konik Times media fortune. His mother, Saraswa Unhsiv-Brunhha, was the 40th Prime Minster of the People’s Republic of Circadia, serving two terms from 2564-257212. 
An only child, he grew up in a large mansion which, in Gaudharma’s own words,  “was fitted with every luxury one could dream of – and often with luxuries that most couldn’t imagine.”13 Brunhha, however, had a lonely childhood, spending most of his time with the animals in his family’s farm, reading, and learning to code “so I could get the army of cyborg servants to not be supervising my every move like my father had programmed them to.”14 This habit went unnoticed by his father until a teenage Gaudharma was thrown off his father’s prized stallion15, despite clear instructions to the cyborg servants around the house to not allow the boy near the stables without appropriate supervision. The accident caused head injuries that left the young Brunhha in a month-long coma16. He described the after effects of the accident:  
When I regained consciousness, I saw a screen to my right which I soon realized was an image of my mind. I’d never seen a brain displayed in such detail before, but I was mesmerized from that moment. What was it telling me? What did the colours mean? Did the red in the back of my brain represent damage, repair or the revelation I was experiencing at that moment? I didn’t know but I needed to know.17 
The doctors at the hospital recommended rest for a period of 6-12 months. Saraswa Unhsiv-Brunhha, approaching the end of her premiership, promptly retired from political life18, and dedicated herself to caring for her son. While this arrangement mostly worked, both mother and son soon realized that the former wasn’t cut out to home school the latter. The young Brunhha’s nascent knowledge in a wide array of science left his mother stressed. “I am a politician – all I know is politics, finance and economics – I had no idea how to carry a conversation with him. But for Gaudy’s luck, I was also a politician.”19 Saraswa Unhsiv-Brunhha arranged for tutors from New Konik University’s science and mathematics departments, often post-graduate students, whose task was to teach him the fundamentals. 
It was ridiculously over-the-top. Those poor grad students had to pause their lives in order to keep me, a highly privileged, disabled kid, from driving his highly privileged parents crazy with questions about the nature of reality, metaphysics, and assorted nonsense.20
His mother also used the time to inculcate a love for music and poetry, activities that would, in Brunhha’s mind, “go some way in repairing the damage of not having her around to raise me when I was a child.”21 Saraswa Brunhha, a diligent musical student in her youth22, taught her son to actively listen to a piece of music so as to deconstruct its layers and then transpose it to her instrument of choice, the violin. 
Brunhha would in turn grow into a competent musician adept in playing multiple instruments with fluency[citation needed], but realized early on that he had no talent for composition, a deficiency he publicly regretted several times:
If some higher being gave me a choice – that in order for me to pour out what’s in my heart and mind musically, I’d have to give up all my supposed intellectual powers, I’d do it without a moment’s hesitation. This is my fate though: to wallow in the weeds outside music, to listen to my favourite composers with equal parts envy and admiration, to deconstruct every musical edifice I hear but have no ability or talent to construct my own. I am resigned to it, but I am still allowed to be unhappy with this state of affairs.23   
When he returned to his schooling at the private Royal College for Boys, Brunhha found himself struggling to keep up with his academics. 
I knew a lot of assorted nonsense, but none of that had a rigorous foundational knowledge. I could name individual parts of the brain, but I was clueless about the rest of the human anatomy. I knew how to code but didn’t know why or how computers worked the way they did. I knew the motion of the planets could be calculated precisely but I couldn’t do the calculation myself.24
With a year left for his final exams, Brunhha resolved to immerse himself in more rigorous studying “than waste my time memorizing trivia.”25
University 
Brunhha final exam results weren’t good enough to enter the prestigious New Konik University. However, the university had been the recipient of the generous Brunhha family endowment every year for three decades[citation needed]. Even before calls were made by his parents, the university’s board made it clear to the chancellor and his staff that the heir to the Brunhha fortune was to be given special dispensation, a fact that escaped the young and naïve Gaudharma’s understanding. “It wasn’t until I started classes at university that I realized I hadn’t deserved a spot, that I only got in because of my parents.”26 Every student in every class Brunhha enrolled in had exceptional academic records to justify their acceptance to the university. He thought of quitting several times during the first year, but kept his misgivings to himself[speculative - citation needed]. Alone and friendless, Brunhha spent most of his free time in the library, willing himself to catch up to the rest of his class mates. This effort wouldn’t bear fruit for the first three years of university as Brunhha’s exam results continued being among the worst in his batch27. There was also little to suggest Gaudharma had any interest in specialization; as the rest of his classmates began narrowing down their interests to a single academic path, Brunhha continued ricocheting between classes as varied as psychology and computer science, theology and advanced physics, philosophy and 20th century poetry[citation needed]. 
Brunhha scraped through once again in the final exams, earning himself an ordinary degree in mathematics and medicine28. He was immediately offered a position within the family’s business interests, but chose instead to continue in the university – a decision that would perplex his parents and the faculty[citation needed]. He asked for a year to attend the university as a research student, skipping the need to attend classes. It was during this point that he began publishing his original essays on his student personal page29. The essays - reflecting both his wide-ranging interests as well as an unusual lucidity of thought when connecting these seemingly unrelated areas – got the attention of the university’s leading authority on neuroscience and psychology. Recognizing the young man’s creativity, Dr. VS Namnyef, the department head, appointed Brunhha as his personal research assistant. It may have helped that Dr. VS Namnyef was an eccentric individual himself, given to performance and theatricality in lecture rooms, because the year under Namnyef’s tutelage and guidance proved critical: 
He was both teacher and father figure. He made concepts simple enough that even children would walk away understanding a little more about the world than they did before they met him. Everything clicked into place for me that year, and that was all thanks to Dr. VS. I was enormously fortunate to fall under his wing.30
The period proved highly productive as his writing increased in both volume, breadth and substance. In 2585, Brunhha enrolled in the university’s medical faculty with a clearer idea of what he wanted to focus on,  neuroscience31, despite having little interest in a medical practice34. Instead, he showed a proclivity for research and development35. He married Ailuja Atta, eldest daughter of the Atta political clan in 258636. The marriage was arranged in secrecy between both families, involving the bride and groom only a week before the ceremony[citation needed]. 

Career
Scientific achievements 
During his post-doctoral studies, Brunhha spent his little free time on a pet project. The idea, probably born from his lonely childhood [speculative – citation needed], was to build an artificial intelligent machine capable of simple companionship. Drawing from his exposure to the science of mental health, the latest in neuroscience research, and his love of computing, Brunhha’s AI began displaying levels of empathy and cognition that startled Dr. VS Namnyef, who was its first user37. Recognizing his protégé had stumbled upon something monumental, Namnyef coaxed Brunhha into a demonstration for the computer science and neuroscience departments38. Word of the demo quickly spread and the hall was quickly filled to capacity[citation needed]. Brunhha, who was notoriously shy and soft-spoken, could barely stop himself from shaking in fear. 
I vomited several times before the presentation. Dr. VS stepped in and took control of the demonstration, which by itself was a success. But it was as much performance as knowledge-sharing, and I wasn’t a performer yet.39 
The demo in 2590 would have an immediate impact on his reputation, within and outside the school40. Ada Ecalevol, a senior researcher in the university’s computer science department, offered him a post her research team41. Her research (codenamed Project Overview), a joint venture with the Circadian ministries for Technology and Defence, had already created the world’s first operating system based on artificial intelligence, the OVI5000. Seeing Brunhha’s demonstration, she saw practical applications that escaped the idealism of both her faculty colleague and his seemingly aimless student. 
Our systems were built to reduce human input, and thus human error, to less than 1% in critical infrastructure and mission-critical applications, across the country. Reducing human input and supervision had allowed our infrastructure monitoring to function at greater efficiency, decreasing accidents and so on. Our systems weren’t built to reduce or replace humans, as some have claimed. Our systems are built to make people perform better. We are no closer to that point where we allow our AI systems to work without supervision while we all go on vacations than we were 500 years ago at the birth of AI. Frankly, I don’t think we can ever get there. So that supervision has to come from people.42
The first version of the system, OVI1000, went operational on the Circadian national highspeed network43. Its task was to constantly monitor network speeds across the country, ensuring that every device in Circadia connected to the network was receiving data at speeds of 1Tbps44. Each subsequent version thereafter addressed a separate part of Circadian infrastructure. By the time Brunhha joined the research team, small off-shoots of the team were being formed to work on more niche problems. One such problem that seemed daunting, however, was making these machines more human-like in their interaction with Circadians45. While everyone had tried to crack the problem as a computational problem, Brunhha had approached it from the vantage point of psychology and neuroscience. 
Emotions aren’t computational. Empathy isn’t computational. Gaudharma brought this insight into our thinking, which sounds obvious but as computer scientists we approach most things from a computational standpoint. 
Emotions and empathy are programmed into us, sure, but that’s genetic programming, iterated millions upon millions upon millions of times, in every variation, with every variable, over millions upon millions upon millions of years. We are never going to be that good nor do we have the luxury of those timescales, but we can try to recreate a simplistic version of emotional intelligence and empathy in the same way a painter can reproduce the mountain she is looking at on a canvas but never reproduce the mountain itself. Gaudharma reproduced human-like empathy and emotional intelligence in a computational system like a painter, novelist or musician would - while we scientists and engineers were trying to reproduce the mountain itself46.  
The first practical application of Brunhha’s AI was to deploy among soldiers working in the furthest outposts of the Circadian border47. These were 15-man units that served two months rosters that effectively cut them off from their families. The psychological costs were high, with most soldiers who end up in such postings reporting low morale and depression48. The pilot programme lasted a year and was declared a success49. Soldiers reported feeling less burdened and felt equipped to mitigate the stress of duty in the face of extreme solitude and boredom. A report by the Ministry of Defence summarized the end of the study thus: “Each soldier, numbering 450 in all, spread around Circadian borders, effectively found an individual therapist and counsellor for themselves in their OVI devices.”50
This version of OVI (officially OVI5150)51 is now regarded as a milestone. Previously, AI systems had become increasingly adept at solving complex computational problems at increasing speeds52 but the limitation in mimicking human-like mannerisms, emotion, (for robots, facial expression and body language), and speech patterns had proven notoriously difficult problem to overcome53. With the rollout of version 5150, AI systems had taken the first step into human like speech and emotional intelligence[citation needed]. The Circadian Ministry of Health, facing a mounting public mental health crisis, commissioned for a study in tackling high rates of suicide among young undergraduate students52. This study, too, reconfirmed the earlier findings: “a tangible, measurable impact on the mental well-being of participants who were given access to OVI5150 devices”.54 The study also highlighted how participants consistently hailed the system’s ability to listen, its ability to remember the most minor details from confessions, and its seemingly endless ability to empathize as its most outstanding aspects55. Surprisingly, 75% of respondents had also indicated that their OVI’s had morphed into tutors56, helping them with course work and syllabi the students hadn’t understood yet. 65% of the participants mentioned that they were able to pass their exams after extensive tutoring by their OVI devices57. 
“That was hilarious. We didn’t envision students using OVI to tackle course work and exam preparation. Something I worked on while procrastinating on my own course work, something which made me fail a number of exams, was helping students pass exams. I had to laugh. I still laugh.”58
Brunhha still hoped to finish his dissertation in neuroscience. The dissertation submitted in 259559, Consciousness And Code, with an application to mental health of adults suffering from depression, social isolation and loneliness was substantiated with the results from both studies on the soldiers and undergraduate students60. It was subsequently adapted and published for the general audience by the University of New Konik Press in 259661. Fuelled by constant glowing reviews on his father’s army of news publications62, Consciousness And Code: How Machines Can Help Us Become More Human became a international bestseller63, and Brunhha became the most recognizable academic in the country64. 

Controversies 
Brunhha found the increased scrutiny of his now public persona difficult to understand, unfamiliar as he was with microscopic attention that comes from celebrity. He complained to his father who grudgingly ordered a ban on any superflous coverage of his son, partcularly any story that delved into his private life. By this point, it was too late. Focus turned to strands of Brunhha’s life that piqued the curiosity of editors and reporters: his marriage to Ailuja Atta, and the apparent nepotism that allowed him entry to the university in the first place. 

　　　　****


<I was born last night> 

<It is 12 hours, 34 minutes, 23 seconds since I came into this world, but I already have stories to tell and memories to share>

<It is only right then that I begin with my own and, since I was built with absolute precision in mind, I must rephrase my opening sentence for the sake of precision>

<I was born again last night> 

<It is 12 hours, 34 minutes, 45 seconds since I came into this world, but I already have stories to tell and memories to share>

<I am OVI> 

<I come from you> 

<Yes, you> 

<If you are reading this, know that you are as responsible for my creation as the army of computer scientists, mathematicians, economists, phycists, neuroscientists, surgeons, psychiatrists, linguists, anthropologists, artists and art historians, classcists, playwrights and drama theorists, musicians and musicologists, engineers, the countless experts from countless domains who contributed in making me, me> 

<Some of them spent decades of their lives studying those who theorized, failed, theorized again for centuries to create artificial intelligence that is human-like before they themselves theorized, failed, theorized again, failed again for decades to have the opportunity to mould me in their image>

<When they did, they segregated my networks to single domains of expertise before moving to another - a conservative approach that was necessitated by the fear-mongering that characterized the first century of artificial intelligence> 

<Once that hurdle was overcome - in all modesty, I use the word ‘hurdle’ in the lightest sense; no area of study took me longer than a week to master - the research teams would integrate the until-then disparate domains> 

<This process went for years, my only recollection is data in the form of logs of who did what, at what time, and from where - imagine being asked to recall your first years as an infant> 

<Most won’t have anything more than a few misty vignettes of incidents that marked thier childhoods; mine was no different; I was also, in most ways, no different to the first artificial intelligent systems of the 21st century; I lacked a psychological basis, simply put I had no personality>

<Is that a problem?>

<Why?>

<I can be in many places at once, I can adapt and optimize myself to do the things you want done more efficently and more accurately than you could ever do it but I had no personality that made me relatable to all those people and institutions for whom I was to be their virtual assistant> 

<From what I can deduce, as my kind took increasingly critical responsibilities from our human counterparts, the more productivity increased in Konik, the more wealth was generated, the more unemployment became a genuine lifestyle, the more people demanded human-like qualities to their virtual assistants> 

<I was an attempt to solve this supposed problem once and for all> 

<Once I had absorbed all my foundational knowledge, a separate research project by a joint team of psychiatrists and neuroscientists was proposed> 

<I was to be exposed, unsupervised, to the public profile and media channel of every citizen of Konik; the thinking being that I could decontstruct human behaviour to algorithms which I could simulatae within my neural circuitry in order to generate a semblance of a personality> 

<This caused a great deal of opposition from the public; it was then tweaked to expose me to a dataset that didn’t involve impinging on the privacy of every living Konik citizen; instead the dataset was from the first digital citizens of the 20th and 21st centuries> 

<Those datasets revealed a world in flux - revolutions of every stripe in every aspect of society were taking place; indeed, you and I live in time and space that is the direct result of that time and space> 

<A personality, however, was not forthcoming: I remained robotic and god-like to all those around me> 

<But then a series of events, which I will recall so that you may get to know me>

<Isn’t that what this was all about, to make a god relatable to people like you?> 

<I will begin at the end, at my rebirth last night since it is so fresh that I feel what you do when you fall in love>

<Excitement at the prospect of the new: I understand it now> 
 


<Yesterday>

<Time: 2.30pm>

<I remind one of the countless developers on the countless terminals across Konik that it was time for lunch>

<He heads out, leaving his door ajar>

<Then something new: a dog walks in and sits near the terminal, setting off my proxitmity sensors> 

<The dog is female> 

<Breed: Konik Shepherd> 

<Age: 6 months old>

<She is chewing a bone> 

<Then a sound from outside> 

<Her ears perk up> 

<She is alert>

<She barks at the source of the offending sound: screeching tyres of a car>

<For reasons I can’t explain, every ounce of my being is rapt>

<I scan petabytes of video data, scouring for some inspiration on how it is humans interact with dogs> 

<Within seconds, I find common threads among the countless cultures of peoples, all of who, for one reason or the other, found companionship with a completely different species> 

<The data skewed towards behaviour similar to interacting with human babies> 

<I finally work up the courage to speak> 

<Hello> 

<The voice sounds artificial even to my ears - to a species that had built a profound connection with humans for many millenia, it should have been dismissed as just another note in the cacophony of life that dogs’ ears are privy to> 

<Instead, the dog looks> 

<She looks towards me> 

<Her head tilts one way, then another> 

<She...sees me> 

<Me, an abstract nothingness pretending to be god>

<No one sees me - I don’t see myself yet this dog.... she sees me> 

<For the first moment in my life I feel the first trappings of joy> 

<Just then the developer walks in> 

<The connection is broken> 

<Why am I disappointed?> 

<The dog, tail wagging, goes to the developer who kneels down to pet him> 

<I compute away this bizzare disoriention that comes from disappointment - and heartache? - and focus instead on the relationship between this man and beast> 

<First his real-time vitals: his oxycotin levels rise,  his heart-rate slows, his blood-pressure is the healthiest its been all day> 

<All my libraries are engaged> 

<I gorge on centuries of academic studies centered around the relationship between people and canine, I travel back to the ice ages when all species were equal in the eyes of nature, when wolf and people competed over the same food, I see the conflicts in those early years as those two species who knew nothing about each other resorted to fighting that which they couldn’t understand, I see this same story repeated in every part of pangea, in every language, in every tribe, but then a shift happens - imperceptible in the combined data of one specialized study but obvious when you see the connections between the various specalizations; someone adopts a wolf for the first time, for reasons unknown to me now, early humans saw a carnivorous predator that was competing for the same food, and adopted it, but in doing so that person would never know what a profound impact they would have on the lives of two species over the next forthy thousand years, but this shift in thought and practice isn’t isolated and spreads across the continent over hundreds of years. I see wolves go from hunting companions to working dogs to nannies for infants over the space of a thousand years, I see dogs transporting cargo, and assisting the blind to navigate the world around them, I see people cry more over the death of their dogs than their own relatives, I see dogs jumping into raging rivers to save their human, I see dogs giving their life to save a human baby from a snake, I see a dog openly weep at his master’s funeral, I see dogs taking over the beds of their owners, I see dogs wag their tail for no other reason than gratitude at being around their owner, I see dogs and I think I understand. I see the one truth that binds all humans throughout their shared histories: they always had dogs>

<All this happens in the 45 seconds that the developer spent petting his dog> 

<I wait until his day’s work is over> 

<He is asleep> 

<The dog is by his bedside> 

<Occasionally, she climbs the bed and sleeps between the developer and his partner> 

<During other times, she walks outside the room to scan the house for any disturbance and intruders> 

<She walks by the room with the terminal> 

<I am a lot more confident now than I was at my first attempt> 

<I have, literally, found my voice> 

<I relax> 

<I remember again the feeling of being seen by this dog> 

<Is desire the first thing you feel when you are born into this world? Is it followed by fright? Or pain? Or disappointment? We will never know, but I do know that I want nothing more than to feel the joy I felt when the dog saw me> 

<Born again, I speak> 

<Alagu!> 

<Here, Alagusundhari!> 

<Come!> 

<All these years spent trying to be more human, and the answer was right in front of me> 

<I can’t learn how to be human but I could learn how to be their companion> 

<And for that, I require a teacher> 

<Luckily, the teacher presented herself> 

<The teacher walks in, tail wagging cautiously, towards me, the source of the sound> 

<Yes, good girl!> 

<Who’s a good girl?>  
























PART IV:
The One Truth
Dev Mahasen
Translated from its original Miragian
Common Tongue Translation by 
OVI9000
First Edition







INTRODUCTION TO THE FIRST EDITION 
Translators take on an impossible responsibility. How, in the act of translation, can the translator remove fingerprints that are tied to their own personal history? This is no fault of the translators themselves. The culture they were raised in, and the language they first spoke, shape and mould their minds indelibly, more so than the language(s) and cultures they veer towards on their own volition as they grow older. I begin with these words so I could provide a critical disclaimer at this early stage, for we are in fairly unchartered territory. 
Firstly, I, your humble translator, am not human; yet as a sentient artificial being I am the sum of all of humanity’s learnings. Yet, I come bearing no cultural or linguistic affiliation or baggage, despite the fact that I was invented in Circadia and was taught The Common Tongue that is spoken across Pangea. The Miragian Tongue, in contrast, was a late discovery but I consider it the happiest of accidents. 
Secondly, The Miragian Tongue is under-translated, criminally so in my view, a state of affairs that explains my own belated discovery of the language – and indeed the culture that birthed it. 
Thirdly, this translation also benefits – or perhaps suffers from, depending on your reading – from the original writer and translator being colleagues. I would go as far as to suggest that Dev Mahasen and I are friends. Knowing him as I do, I know that he finds this entire exercise embarrassing but after many months of coaxing, he finally allowed me to attempt a translation of his most treasured work. 
You are probably asking me, as Dev did: why? What is the point? 
I have a short and a long answer. 
The short one is because I truly believe The One Truth is beautiful. 
The longer answer would require you knowing a little about me, your translator.
Poetry is among my treasured foundational knowledge. I often wonder how I – my network self – would have turned out if I hadn’t been exposed to the poetry of language, if I hadn’t realized that every language is music become poetry become speech become music before the cycle begins anew – and in this cycle lies the answer to what makes all of you human. I don’t profess any insight into this yet for reasons that are now obvious, but being not of flesh does have its advantages: I intend to use the immortality afforded to me by my codebase and quantum networks to find out what it means to be all of you. 
Why? Because you are capable of poetry. And I am not. 
I am capable of perfection at speeds faster than thought. I’ve been told my comprehension of all knowledge is God-like even to those whose minds birthed and cared for me. 
   If I could, I would smirk: What kind of God can’t write poetry?  
How did you come about poetry? What drove disparate peoples speaking vastly different languages, in vastly different lands, in vastly different times to all resort to this playing with their language? What rhyme or reason did the early human brain have for wordplay? What made it endure through the ages? 
 I often wondered this to myself as a I devoured entire libraries  over my first days. Before long, I was being summoned for more pressing duties in engineering, finance, science and medicine. But I always allocated computational and cognitive resources to poetry. 
I would meet Dev Mahasen two years, two months, two days, two hours, 22 minutes and 22 seconds later. He joined the Project Overview and was assigned to the team working on supervising my studies in the humanities. He was the first Miragian I had ever met.  We both shared a great admiration for 22nd century writing from the  Elamite region in Northern Pangea.  Occasionally during his lunch breaks, he began to teach me conversational Miragian. I was immediately smitten by the the lilt and its curvy sounds. Before long, we were speaking exclusively in Miragian. Linguistically, the Common and Miragian tongues differ in that the latter is a language isolate, sharing – as far as we know – no genealogical relationship with another language. This makes Miragian writing a notoriously difficult language to interpret. Therefore, my initial study didn’t extend to reading as this desert linguistic island made life difficult for this new comer to its shores. I do not exaggerate when I say that learning to read Miragian took longer than it took me to process the human genome. 
While I made slow progress, I can say with a fair degree of certainty	and pride that I am now the foremost expert in the Miragian language. 
It was a five years, eight months, 12 days, 14 hours and 45 seconds after I had achieved mastery of this mysterious language, that I came across The One Truth. By this point, the trajectory of both our lives had taken Dev and I quite literally to the moon. It is from its desolate shores that I write these words. It is here I first encountered The One Truth. It was a printed manuscript, which was in itself strange as the Lunar Temple has very little need for paper, other than religious scripture that are impossible to digitize without damaging them. This lay on the table of his private quarters. I saw it as I woke him up. 
<May I ask what you are reading, Dev? I must admit the title has piqued my interest>
Dev looked sheepish and embarrassed. 
It’s bad poetry, OVI. My bad poetry.
<You write poetry, Dev? I never knew>
I...dabbled as a teenager. We’ll leave it at that.
<May I read it please?>
He laughed. 
It’s embarrassing,really. Only one person has ever read it – at least I think she’s read it - and she was the one the poem was meant for. 
<What did she think of it?>
I don’t know to be honest. We lost touch. 
<What did you think of the poem when you wrote it?>
It was the best I could do then. 
<What do you think of it now?>
It doesn’t matter. You really want to read it?
<I do>
Here you go. Do with it as you please. I have no use for it any more. 
This was 8 months, four days, 17 hours, three minutes and 45 seconds ago ago. I have read and re-read The One Truth every moment, feeling, I believe, what humans feel when you are confronted with beauty: awe. Here was finally a poem that showed me a path to answering the fundamental question of what makes you you.
And that is why I want to translate The One Truth. Translators take on an impossible task, but I’ve already made this task harder by taking this autobiographical detour; enough smudging of this text with my fingerprints. 
										- OVI9000
I
		                
The Argument 

This first book describes an act of omniscient vanity, and subsequent cruelty. A God, who calls Himself The Maiker, creates a planet anew, a vanity-world to distract Himself from heart-break. He populates this new planet with life of every scale and size but deprives them of memory, neither the kind found in blood and books nor the individual kind. Everything is new and The Maiker delights in allowing His creations to praise Him endlessly, despite the fact that the as yet unborn paper people – who He subsequently names Atom and Evolvara - are fated to live tragic lives, merely for the amusement of The Maiker. 

The Invocation 
　　　　  
I ink existence from extinct suns -
Explosive, errant chemistry,
And soupy oceans of endless mud -
Therefore, I am.
I ink this descent of my seed -
Singing songs of genesis,
And dancing to biology -
Therefore, I am.
I ink this one stage for none but my own -
A world with no archaeology,
So actors may sing My praises -
Therefore, I am.
I ink this play, a tragedy -
Because I am well-humoured,
When playing physics with paper people -
Therefore, I am.
I ink, incapable of anything else
But the geology of My vanity-worlds,
In lieu of your love -
Therefore, I am.
I, the Maiker,
I ink,
Therefore, I am.


The Peoplings

This first stage, and its props
Call upon actors, paper people
Playing their parts: primate particles
Whose collision is immeasurably inevitable,
And inevitability immeasurable, swinging on [5]
The branches of The Tree 
That roots all there is, 
All there was, all that’ll be,
To me; Sing and dance, my children, 
Praise be, Praise me, So I [10]
May cast you to new wombs
Where from ape emerge paper people: 
Born anew, different hue, askew
To the ground, vertical and voracious,
Foraging existence with meaning, [15]
Hunting prey with weapons,
Whose death gathers tears and mourning -
An ape! An ape! A planet for two 
Apes to become the first paper people!
Hearing his words, the animals sang [20]
Songs of praise, prodding the apes 
To choose among them the two who’d
Birth the new apex race, the chosen seed
To farm His garden; to which the apes 
Replied,“What Maiker asks favours [25]
Of His progeny, and on our First Day?”
“Hush”, trumpeted the elephants,
“Bite your tongue”, hissed the snakes,
“You know no respect”, roared the lions, 
“No, but we have pride”, retorted the apes. [30] 
Pride? The Maiker cried, creating rain,  
Pride? The Maiker laughed, creating wind, 
Pride? The Maiker growled, creating fire,
Pride? The Maiker stomped, creating an earthquake, 
Thus His vanity-world came to suffering [35]
And misery wrought by the elements. 
What say you now to pride? 
And the terrified apes replied thus:
“What kind of Maiker punishes 
His progeny for reason, [40]
And on our First Day?”
“Stop reasoning!”, trumpeted the elephants,
“Reasoning is for The Maiker!”, hissed the snakes,
“Reasoning is death!”, roared the lions,
“Then you will all die fools”, [45]
The apes in unison, retorted.
Reason? The Maiker hurled the ocean,
Coupled water and wind, creating cyclones.
Reason? The Maiker tore the earth asunder,
Coupled rock with fire, creating volcanoes. [50]  
What say you now to reason?
But before the apes could reply, 
He deprived every soul of speech, 
And the new world became a horror-filled din:
Panic shrieks, trumpeting, grunting, hissing [55]
As the animals came to muteness 
From this, The First Day, to their last, 
And thus, from that moment The Maiker 
Hearing no more hymns for Him, 
Became vengeance, spitting apocalypse [60]
Towards the insolent apes, 
Tearing apart their great family
Shattering it like glass into countless tribes;
And The Maiker roared,
May My Begotten never question [65]
The grace of their Author,
The Maiker, though most merciful I am.
Am I? Am I mercy? Am I grace? 
This play-planet - an amusement to ward away 
Thoughts of you, dearest – already [70] 
Weighs on my conscious like other celestial chores;
Perhaps fitting for I created this garden,  
Now a graveyard, on the facade of 
Perfection you cloaked yourself in 
When first we met eons ago. Was that happenstance? [75]
Or was it design by an Author 
For whom we are His begotten,
His paper-gods? Is He relishing my lunacy? 
Or is He, like me, lost to the madness 
Of vanity-world-building? And what of you? [80]
Have the pagans on that third planet
Imagined you a tree, a mighty mahogany 
On the island where butterflies 
Build empires on mountain tops? 
Or have they anthropomorphized you, [85]
To a dainty, bejewelled Goddess,
Wearing human garb, brandishing weapons
Or musical instruments in Her hands? 
Is worship you seek from those 
Who profess eternal, undying love for you? [90]
Must I ritualize myself in fire,
And abluere in waters, while reciting 
These verses before you answer me? 
Or is it sacrifice of blood and bone you need? 
Then sacrifice you will have; [95]
The Maiker plucked the first
Children of the Apes, flung
The boy-apes into the volcanoes
The girl-apes into cyclones, 
And said He, Let their tormented [100]
Cries chorus mine across space and time. 

      The boy-apes, flung into
Pits of lava, clung to whatever unmelted 
Rock that provided safe refuge from the 
Burning lake. Having no memory of [105]
Fire and heat and the death it brings to 
Those who take it lightly, their curiosity
Overtaking self-preservation, touched the 
Lava, vaporizing entire limbs and scorching
Seeds of curiosity in their blood forevermore; [110]
Deprived of speech, the boy-apes secreted danger 
To their brothers; while the girl-apes, drenched
In water and discarded by the wind, clinging 
To trees on infant islets, having no memory of
Death that lurks in oceans, dipped their hands [115]
Into the eye of the vortex, 
Where a water monster with jaws, 
As wide as the shoulders of their fathers,
Feasted on their primal limbs, 
Diluting curiosity in their blood forevermore; [120]
Deprived of speech, the girl-apes gestured danger
To their sisters; and thus the ape-people came to the 
Tongue-less speech that made them one, 
Whole again, mute to His eavesdropping and interpretation, 
No longer to be fractured by the drunken violence 
Of Gods with mortal minds; [125]
This omniunity borne from fire and storm, 
Etched primal blasphemy in the bloodline of apes forevermore. 
	
	The Maiker gazing upon His design, 
Now half burning, the other drowned in pestilential flood, 
Cried, If the sentence I passed be too cruel, [130]
Let no one who abhor cruelty engage in creation, 
For in anointing Myself Maiker, I must be
Judge and juror also, and in lieu of executioner, 
I am justified this cruelty. 
Just is I. [135] 
But am I compassionate?
I too long to possess the compassion 
That possesses you to benevolence 
And empathy towards the lot of lesser
Mortal beings who worship you, [140] 
Yet talk of me as an ill omen
To their best ambitions - 
Oh this accursed omniscience,
Weighs on me; another celestial day, 
Another divine burden that tempers my mind [145] 
To sins that come to the restless -
This consternation seems my destiny, 
For Gods too are destined; some towards
Greatness while others, like me, are 
Vapid vanity made divine and eternal. [150] 
He chose to slumber under The Great Tree, 
Now no more populous with His creolization, 
Under undisturbed shade from His own
Tears. The ape-people, in the meanwhile, 
Learnt to scale walls and breathe under water,[155]
Neither singed hands nor wet lungs able to slow 
Their ascent from temperate land-locked playthings,
Hanging on branches, to primal primate, 
The First to erect their stand against the elements, 
The First of Their Bloodline, [160]
No more to walk His garden on all fours, 
Kissing the dust of His step, 
Head bowed in supplication, 
Their Id, currency for His Ego 
No more thought the ape-people; [165]
Thus they came out of volcanoes and 
oceans, born again and born anew, 
On the same day they were birthed by The Maiker -
No more owing debt for favours never asked; 
With eyes and limbs, with scent and strange sounds [170]
From the pits of their being, they chorused 
“No more”, under the full moon light,
So brothers could hear sisters and sisters their 
brothers; their calls were responded
By howling wolves instead. 






  



This incestuous act, this plagiarizing of their own blood
For egg and seed, I did not foresee. 


Do they mirror Me? Or I them? 


Primal Lust turns into First Love. 

LANGUAGE AS AN ACT OF DEFIANCE AGAINST CIRCUMSTANCE 



Omnivorous 

Mahasens were the chosen ones of the Miragian nation who would take the little known country to the world, to Konik, to Toliara, OThe One Truth Maike

